{"id":14881832,"mediaExerciseId":"e4dd7834-dde8-4014-ad28-6250d35d732b","exerciseName":"16","chapterName":"23","chapterTitle":"Enterprise Risk Management","groupId":612487,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":787,"solutions":[{"id":6009057,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will discuss the similarities between the concept of a rider in an insurance policy and option terms. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"To give a brief introduction of the proper terms, we can first define them. A rider is a term in insurance that refers to the amendments or policy provision for a specific term in the insurance. This means that it is a way to protect the policy holder from future risks. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The \"rider\" can be classified as a **put option** since if the market price is higher than the price I bought the couch, I will not exercise my put option. I will only exercise this if for example, the price depreciates to $\\$300$ as stated in the problem. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"b5219eb3-8e5d-445b-b69d-9e52664a7e36","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","v